attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This MIPS-based ELF binary is a malicious IoT botnet agent, specifically a variant of Mirai or Gafgyt. It contains multiple DDoS attack modules, including SSDP amplification (evidenced by the M-SEARCH discovery strings in sub_407868) and various UDP/TCP flooding functions (sub_401f58, sub_4022a8, sub_403e50). The sample features hardcoded User-Agents for HTTP attacks, obfuscated protocol strings (e.g., /x38/xFJ...), and a hardcoded Command & Control (C2) IP address: 151.243.109.76 (found in sub_409784). It also implements daemonization by redirecting I/O to /dev/null and utilizes custom XOR-like encoding (sub_40a7d4) for its internal strings.
